<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06091008 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06091008 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Associated Press; FRESH APPROACH -- Inkatha Freedom Party leaderMangosuthu Buthelezi, left, and the ANC's Nelson Mandela meet to discuss theviolence between their rival parties.  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  SOUTH-AFRICA; BLACK; LEADER; MEETING; PEACE; PLANNING  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Black leaders Nelson Mandela and Mangosuthu Buthelezi emerged from a 51/2-hour &quot;emergency meeting&quot; Saturday to announce a fresh initiative to endthe bloodshed that has reignited between their followers in recent weeks.;   Both leaders are scrambling to find some way to end the resurgent carnage,which has all but scuttled the &quot;peace initiative&quot; they announced two monthsago and led to fears that the violence has spiraled beyond their control.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  A NEW TRY FOR PEACE IN S. AFRICAMANDELA, BUTHELEZI VOW TO WORK TOGETHER  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Mandela, deputy president of the African National Congress, and Buthelezi,the chief minister of the Inkatha Freedom Party, said that as a result oftheir latest &quot;man-to-man&quot; meeting, the two groups would better coordinatetheir efforts to inform their supporters of the need to end the killing.;   More than 1,200 people have died in black factional fighting in South Africa'stownships since last August, largely in bloodshed between ANC supporters andfollowers of the more conservative, Zulu-dominated Inkatha.;    After Mandelaand Buthelezi announced their initiative plan at their first meeting in lateJanuary, the peace held for several weeks. But beginning early this month inSoweto, the black township outside Johannesburg, there have been several,fresh outbreaks of fighting.;    A clash between police and ANC supportersleft more than a dozen dead in Daveyton township west of Johannesburg, andmore than two weeks of clashes in Johannesburg's Alexandra township ended withthe slaughter of 15 people at a funeral vigil last week.;    The most recentviolence has erupted in Natal province, Inkatha's home base, where 19 peoplehave died since Thursday.;    Concerns about the two leaders' ability to endthe violence has been intensified because much of the recent killing hasoccurred either during or just after &quot;peace meetings&quot; held by one group or theother.;    Those who expected an immediate end to the fighting were &quot;naive,&quot;Mandela said.;    &quot;We never expected one meeting to solve the problem,&quot; hesaid.;    Buthelezi conceded that both leaders are &quot;in a need of showing thatwhen we act together things do happen&quot; -- but he stressed that even they couldnot end the killing alone.;    &quot;We knew the violence was virtually endemic insome areas and that the cult of violence was firmly established in a number ofplaces,&quot; he said. &quot;There is a South Africa out there which is breedingviolence. It must be stamped out.&quot;;    The meeting was delayed for two hoursafter someone telephoned Johannesburg's international airport and said a bombhad been planted on Mandela's jet. A search turned up no such device.;   Mandela praised police for their caution. &quot;It was the proper thing to do,&quot; hesaid.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  RICK LYMAN, Knight-Ridder News Service  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Johannesburg, South Africa  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910331  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Sunday  </DAY><MONTH>  March  </MONTH><PG.COL>  10A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  460  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Sunday March 31, 199100091008,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>